commitResults.messageBody:
Add documentation
Add DukeList class to store user texts
Change Duke implementation by implementing more methods

Add new class, Task, to represent tasks
Add documentation for Task class
Expand DukeList methods implementation

Add new class, ToDo, to specify a task with no date and time
Add new class, Deadline, to specify a task to be done before a specific time
Add new class, Event, to specify a task with a specific start and end time
Modified DukeList, Duke, Task, classes to integrate inheritance of 3 new classes from the Task class
Edit text-ui-test scripts to automate testing of Duke

Change Duke to Duchess in file names for more accurate naming
Add new class, DuchessException, to handle exceptions related to Duchess
Update test scripts to handle more specific error checking

Add deletion of tasks to Duchess
Change array implementation in DuchessList to ArrayList<Task>
Update test scripts to test for deletion
Use enumerations in Duchess to encapsulate the commands used by Duchess

Duchess does not store a user's tasks after execution.

This behaviour is unideal as it limits Duchess' functionality.

Let's add Save and Load functionality to Duchess to allow her to
remember user's tasks after exiting from the interface. Make use
of existing Java libraries (File, FileWriter) to implement this.

Duchess stores dates as string.

This behaviour is unideal as it limits Duchess' functionality.

Let's change the string implementation to a LocalDateTime one so
Duchess can become more useful, providing more specific date formats
and performing more calendar type operations.

Logic for numerous different classes are handled by Duchess.

This is unfavourable as it does not follow the OOP paradigm.

Let's create separate classes Command, Ui, and Parser to handle
their own separate logic apart from Duchess, so Duchess can have
more succinct and readable code.

Duchess's classes are not in any package.

This is undesirable as the project grows as the number of classes
would make it messy and disorganized.

Let's organize the classes into packages meaningfully labelled with
their own purposes.

Duchess uses I/O redirection to test.

This is undesirable as the project grows and the texts become
more complex and difficult to compare with the expected output.

Let's implement JUnit Tests to test the behaviour of the code.
Let's add Test classes for the different classes within Duchess and
package them into respective packages.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add A-Jar. Create a JAR File
commitResults.messageBody:
Duchess does not have an executable JAR file to be distributed
easily.

This is undesirable as it limits the functionality and portability
of Duchess.

Let's package the app as an executable JAR file and release it to
GitHub for others to use.

Duchess' codebase is extensive and will continue to grow as
functionality grows.

Let's add JavaDoc comments to improve readability of code.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add A-CodingStandard: Follow the Coding Standard

commitResults.messageBody:
Duchess stores a list of tasks from the user to display using list.

This can be further improved by limiting the tasks shown using a
search filter.

Let's implement a Find feature to only list out tasks which have
a certain keyword.
